  {
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Both methods currently expect you to call a callback to continue the initial flow. It you just define them with a `noop`, everything is broken :p.\n\nI feel like they should have a similar naming for that reason.\n\nActually, on a broader topic I feel like we have three kind of methods:\n- The event, that you can just listen to and react to, but in a \"forked\" workflow. Like the `on('render')`.\n- The method getting a value as input ( `transformData`) and expecting you to return a new version of the data\n- The method with a callback as input, expecting you to call it when you're done to resume the normal workflow\n\nMy point is that we should be able to clearly know which kind of method we're dealing with from their name. Do you think that would be a good idea?\n\nWe could still maintain backward compatibility by keeping the old names.\n",
    "created_at": "2016-03-08T16:31:34Z",
